<exploration xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="PA-5-2" permid="udB">
  <p permid="hPj">
    Consider the function <m>A</m> defined by the rule
    <me permid="NWs">
      A(x) = \int_1^x f(t) \, dt
    </me>,
    where <m>f(t) = 4-2t</m>.

    <ol label="a." permid="soo">
      <li permid="Yvx">
        <p permid="dfq">
          Compute <m>A(1)</m> and <m>A(2)</m> exactly.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li permid="ECG">
        <p permid="Jmz">
          Use the First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to find a formula for <m>A(x)</m> that does not involve integrals.
          That is,
          use the first FTC to evaluate <m>\int_1^x (4-2t) \, dt</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li permid="kJP">
        <p permid="ptI">
          Observe that <m>f</m> is a linear function;
          what kind of function is <m>A</m>?
        </p>
      </li>

      <li permid="QQY">
        <p permid="VAR">
          Using the formula you found in (b) that does not involve integrals,
          compute <m>A'(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li permid="wYh">
        <p permid="BIa">
          While we have defined <m>f</m> by the rule <m>f(t) = 4-2t</m>,
          it is equivalent to say that <m>f</m> is given by the rule <m>f(x) = 4 - 2x</m>.
          What do you observe about the relationship between <m>A</m> and <m>f</m>?
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
</exploration>

